1) What is JIT compiler in Java?
-->The Just-In-Time (JIT) compiler is a critical component of the Java Runtime Environment (JRE)
    that improves performance by converting Java bytecode into native machine code at runtime.

2) Why is JIT compiler used?
-->A Just-In-Time (JIT) compiler is primarily used to optimize the runtime performance of programs
  by combining the flexibility of interpretation with the speed of compiled code. It is a core component of modern execution environments like the
    The JIT compiler is used for the following specific reasons:

    Performance Optimization: Instead of interpreting bytecode line-by-line repeatedly (which is slow), 
    the JIT compiler translates frequently used code blocks—known as "hotspots"—into native machine code that the CPU can execute directly.


3) When does JIT compile code?
-->Just-In-Time (JIT) compilation occurs during the execution of a program at runtime.

4) How does JIT improve performance?
-->A Just-In-Time (JIT) compiler improves performance by translating bytecode into native
    machine code at runtime, rather than interpreting it, allowing frequently executed "hotspot" code to run much faster.

5) What is the difference between interpreter and JIT?
-->An interpreter translates and executes code line-by-line during runtime, while a JIT (Just-In-Time)
    compiler translates chunks of code into native machine code before execution to improve performance. 

6) What are the types of JIT optimizations?
-->Just-In-Time (JIT) optimization techniques are used by virtual machines (like the JVM or .NET CLR)
  to compile frequently used bytecode into native machine code at runtime, often achieving performance that rivals or exceeds static compilation. 
  These optimizations can be categorized into several key types based on their scope and approach:
  1. Fundamental & Code Generation Optimizations
  Method Inlining: This is considered the "mother of all optimizations," where a method call is replaced directly
  by the body of the called method, reducing call overhead and enabling further optimizations.

  Dead Code Elimination: Identifying and removing code that does not affect the program's results 
  (e.g., unreachable code or unused variables).

  2. Loop Optimizations
  Loop Unrolling: Reducing loop overhead by expanding the body of the loop, reducing the number of times the loop condition is checked.

  3. Dynamic & Profile-Guided Optimizations (JIT-Specific)
  These techniques rely on information gathered while the program is running ("hot spots"). 
  Inline Caching/Speculative Optimization: When calling a virtual method, the JIT observes which concrete
  class is used 99% of the time, speculatively inlines it, and inserts a "guard check" to de-optimize if a different class appears.
